  "@type": "SolutionRecord",
  "@id": "ocp:sep/physics-holism",
  "meta": {
    "title": "Holism and Nonseparability in Physics",
    "description": "It has sometimes been suggested that quantum phenomena exhibit a characteristic holism or nonseparability, and that this distinguishes quantum from classical physics. One puzzling quantum phenomenon arises when one performs measurements on certain separated quantum systems. The results of some such measurements regularly exhibit patterns of statistical correlation that resist traditional causal explanation. Some have held that it is possible to understand these patterns as instances or consequences of quantum holism or nonseparability. Just what holism and nonseparability are supposed to be has not always been made clear, though, and each of these notions has been understood in different ways. Moreover, while some have taken holism and nonseparability to come to the same thing, others have thought it important to distinguish the two. Any evaluation of the significance of quantum holism and/or nonseparability must rest on a careful analysis of these notions and their physical applications.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T05:13:35.308Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T05:13:35.308Z",
    "datePublished": "1999-07-21T14:00:00.000Z",
